# Intuition
Just move every rows in a map and count them then compare it with the cols,if they are equals then increase the result value


# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. If i did it in brute force approach then we have to take a row and compare it with all the columns (comparing done by element by element) so the total time complexity would be $$O(n^3)$$ (n*n for compare row and col and n * n *n to compare element by element)
2. But In optimal approach we store the row-wise value as a string format in a map,But we have to join the numbers by some special character like ($$#,$,@ etc$$) cause lets take a case a row-wise value is 2,2,1,0 and if i joined it without special char then the string would be like "2211" and suppose in col-wise the value is 22,1,1 and after joining without special chars the string would be like "2211",Now both the strings are same and it will increase our result,but thats not true. So thats why we put a special char between every number.
3. After apply the logic the strings look like this row-wise="2@2@1@1" col-wise="22@1@1" ,now both are not same.




# Complexity
- Time complexity:Brute force->$$O(n^3)$$
                  Optimal approach->$$O(n^2)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:$$O(n)$$ for storing the rows in a map
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
``` c++ []
class Solution {
public:
    int equalPairs(vector<vector<int>>& grid) {
        int ans=0;
        unordered_map<string,int> map;
        for(vector<int> row:grid){
            string res="";
            for(int ele:row){
                res+=to_string(ele);
                res+='#';
            }
            map[res]++;
        }
        for(int j=0;j<grid[0].size();j++){
            string res=""; 
            for(int i=0;i<grid.size();i++){
                res+=to_string(grid[i][j]);
                res+='#';
            }
            ans+=map[res];
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```
