# Approach
1. Initialize a variable count to keep track of the number of equal pairs.
2. Iterate over each row in the grid.
3. For each row, iterate over each column in the grid.
4. Compare the current row with the corresponding column using the getColumn helper function.
5. If the row and column are equal (i.e., they contain the same elements in the same order), increment the count variable.
6. After iterating over all rows and columns, return the final value of count.

The getColumn helper function extracts the elements from a specific column in the grid and returns them as a separate vector. It loops over each row and retrieves the element at the specified column index, constructing a vector representing the column.

By comparing each row with each corresponding column, the solution correctly counts the number of pairs where a row and column are equal.



# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int equalPairs(vector<vector<int>>& grid) {
        int n = grid.size();
        int count = 0;

        for (int row = 0; row < n; row++) {
            for (int col = 0; col < n; col++) {
                if (grid[row] == getColumn(grid, col))
                    count++;
            }
        }

        return count;
    }

private:
    vector<int> getColumn(const vector<vector<int>>& grid, int col) {
        vector<int> column;
        for (int i = 0; i < grid.size(); i++) {
            column.push_back(grid[i][col]);
        }
        return column;
    }
};

```

